015/**
016 * Simple hashing functions that we can rely on staying the same cross-platform.
017 * The static methods of this class (not its inner classes) use a custom algorithm
018 * designed for speed and general-purpose usability, but not cryptographic security;
019 * this algorithm is sometimes referred to as Hive, and several other algorithms are
020 * available in static inner classes, some of which have different goals, such as
021 * reduced likelihood of successfully reversing a hash, or just providing another
022 * choice. The hashes this returns are always 0 when given null to hash. Arrays with
023 * identical elements of identical types will hash identically. Arrays with identical
024 * numerical values but different types will sometimes hash differently. This class
025 * always provides 64-bit hashes via hash64() and 32-bit hashes via hash(), and some
026 * of the algorithms here may provide a hash32() method that matches older behavior
027 * and uses only 32-bit math. The hash64() and hash() methods, at least in Wisp and
028 * Mist, use 64-bit math even when producing 32-bit hashes, for GWT reasons. GWT
029 * doesn't have the same behavior as desktop and Android applications when using ints
030 * because it treats doubles mostly like ints, sometimes, due to it using JavaScript.
031 * If we use mainly longs, though, GWT emulates the longs with a more complex
032 * technique behind-the-scenes, that behaves the same on the web as it does on
033 * desktop or on a phone. Since CrossHash is supposed to be stable cross-platform,
034 * this is the way we need to go, despite it being slightly slower.
035 * <br>
036 * There are several static inner classes in CrossHash: Lightning, Falcon, and Mist,
037 * each providing different hashing properties, as well as the inner IHasher interface and a
038 * compatibility version of Wisp as a subclass. Older versions of SquidLib encouraged using a
039 * subclass because the non-nested-class methods used a lousy implementation of the FNV-1a algorithm,
040 * which was roughly 10x slower than the current methods in CrossHash and had poor correlation
041 * properties. In the current version, you probably will be fine with the default functions in
042 * CrossHash, using the Wisp algorithm. If you need a salt to alter the hash function,
043 * using one of a large family of such functions instead of a single function like Wisp, then Mist
044 * is a good choice. Lightning is mostly superseded by Wisp, but it can have better behavior on some
045 * collections regarding collisions; Falcon is meant to be a faster version of Lightning.
046 * <br>
047 * IHasher values are provided as static fields, and use Wisp to hash a specific type or fall
048 * back to Object.hashCode if given an object with the wrong type. IHasher values are optional
049 * parts of OrderedMap, OrderedSet, Arrangement, and the various classes that use Arrangement
050 * like K2 and K2V1, and allow arrays to be used as keys in those collections while keeping
051 * hashing by value instead of the normal hashing by reference for arrays. You probably won't
052 * ever need to make a class that implements IHasher yourself; for some cases you may want to
053 * look at the {@link Hashers} class for additional functions.
054 * <br>
055 * The inner classes provide alternate, faster hashing algorithms. Lightning, Wisp, and Falcon
056 * have no theoretical basis or grounds in any reason other than empirical testing for why they
057 * do what they do, and this seems to be in line with many widely-used hashes (see: The Art of
058 * Hashing, http://eternallyconfuzzled.com/tuts/algorithms/jsw_tut_hashing.aspx ). That said, Wisp
059 * performs very well, ahead of Arrays.hashCode (10.5 ms instead of 15 ms) for over a million
060 * hashes of 16-element long arrays, not including overhead for generating them, while SipHash and
061 * FNV-1a take approximately 80 ms and 135-155 ms, respectively, for the same data). Lightning and
062 * Falcon perform less-well, with Lightning taking 17 ms instead of 15 ms for Arrays.hashCode, and
063 * Falcon taking about 12.3 ms but slowing down somewhat if a 32-bit hash is requested from long
064 * data. All of these have good, low, collision rates on Strings and long arrays. Sketch is only
065 * slightly slower than Wisp, but offers little to no advantage over it yet.
066 * <br>
067 * Mist is a variant on Wisp with 128 bits for a salt-like modifier as a member variable, which can
068 * make 2 to the 128 individual hashing functions from one set of code, and uses 64 bits for some other
069 * hashes (only calls to hash() with data that doesn't involve long or double arrays). Mist has some
070 * minor resemblance to a cryptographic hash, but is not recommended it for that usage. It is,
071 * however ideal for situations that show up often in game development where end users may be able
072 * to see and possibly alter some information that you don't want changed (i.e. save data stored on
073 * a device or in the browser's LocalStorage). If you want a way to verify the data is what you
074 * think it is, you can store a hash, using one of the many-possible hash functions this can
075 * produce, somewhere else and verify that the saved data has the hash it did last time; if the
076 * exact hashing function isn't known (or exact functions aren't known) by a tampering user,
077 * then it is unlikely they can make the hash match even if they can edit it. Mist is slightly slower
078 * than Wisp, at about 18 ms for Mist for the same data instead of Wisp's 10.5, but should never be
079 * worse than twice as slow as Arrays.hashCode, and is still about three times faster than the similar
080 * SipHash that SquidLib previously had here.
081 * <br>
082 * All of the hashes used here have about the same rate of collisions on identical data
083 * (testing used Arrays.hashCode, all the hashes in here now, and the now-removed SipHash), with
084 * any fluctuation within some small margin of error. Wisp (typically via the non-nested methods
085 * in CrossHash) and Mist are the two most likely algorithms you might use here.
086 * <br>
087 * To help find patterns in hash output in a visual way, you can hash an x,y point, take the bottom 24 bits,
088 * and use that as an RGB color for the pixel at that x,y point. On a 512x512 grid of points, the patterns
089 * in Arrays.hashCode and the former default CrossHash algorithm (FNV-1a) are evident, and Sip (implementing
090 * SipHash) did approximately as well as Lightning, with no clear patterns visible (Sip has been removed from
091 * SquidLib because it needs a lot of code and is slower than all of the current hashes). The idea is from
092 * <a href="http://www.clockandflame.com/media/Goulburn06.pdf">a technical report on visual uses for hashing (PDF)</a>.
093 * <ul>
094 * <li>{@link java.util.Arrays#hashCode(int[])}: http://i.imgur.com/S4Gh1sX.png</li>
095 * <li>{@link CrossHash#hash(int[])}: http://i.imgur.com/x8SDqvL.png</li>
096 * <li>(Former) CrossHash.Sip.hash(int[]): http://i.imgur.com/keSpIwm.png</li>
097 * <li>{@link CrossHash.Lightning#hash(int[])}: http://i.imgur.com/afGJ9cA.png</li>
098 * </ul>
099 * <br>
100 * Note: This class was formerly called StableHash, but since that refers to a specific
101 * category of hashing algorithm that this is not, and since the goal is to be cross-
102 * platform, the name was changed to CrossHash.
103 * Note 2: FNV-1a was removed from SquidLib on July 25, 2017, and replaced as default with Wisp; Wisp
104 * was later replaced as default by Hive, and in June 2019 Hive was replaced by Water. Wisp was used
105 * because at the time SquidLib preferred 64-bit math when math needed to be the same across platforms;
106 * math on longs behaves the same on GWT as on desktop, despite being slower. Hive passed an older version
107 * of SMHasher, a testing suite for hashes, where Wisp does not (it fails just like Arrays.hashCode()
108 * does). Hive uses a cross-platform subset of the possible 32-bit math operations when producing 32-bit 
109 * hashes of data that doesn't involve longs or doubles, and this should speed up the CrossHash.Hive.hash()
110 * methods a lot on GWT, but it slows down 32-bit output on desktop-class JVMs. Water became the default
111 * when newer versions of SMHasher showed that Hive wasn't as high-quality as it had appeared, and the
112 * recently-debuted wyhash by Wang Yi, a variation on a hash called MUM, opened some possibilities for
113 * structures that are simple but also very fast. Water is modeled after wyhash and uses the same constants
114 * in its hash64() methods, but avoids the 128-bit multiplication that wyhash uses. Because both wyhash and
115 * Water operate on 4 items at a time, they tend to be very fast on desktop platforms, but Water probably
116 * won't be amazing at GWT performance.
117 * <br>
118 * Created by Tommy Ettinger on 1/16/2016.
119 * @author Tommy Ettinger
120 */

316    /**
317     * An interface that can be used to move the logic for the hashCode() and equals() methods from a class' methods to
318     * an implementation of IHasher that certain collections in SquidLib can use. Primarily useful when the key type is
319     * an array, which normally doesn't work as expected in Java hash-based collections, but can if the right collection
320     * and IHasher are used. See also {@link Hashers} for additional implementations, some of which need dependencies on
321     * things the rest of CrossHash doesn't, like a case-insensitive String hasher/equator that uses RegExodus to handle
322     * CharSequence comparison on GWT.
323     */
324    public interface IHasher extends Serializable {
325        /**
326         * If data is a type that this IHasher can specifically hash, this method should use that specific hash; in
327         * other situations, it should simply delegate to calling {@link Object#hashCode()} on data. The body of an
328         * implementation of this method can be very small; for an IHasher that is meant for byte arrays, the body could
329         * be: {@code return (data instanceof byte[]) ? CrossHash.Lightning.hash((byte[]) data) : data.hashCode();}
330         *
331         * @param data the Object to hash; this method should take any type but often has special behavior for one type
332         * @return a 32-bit int hash code of data
333         */
334        int hash(final Object data);
335
336        /**
337         * Not all types you might want to use an IHasher on meaningfully implement .equals(), such as array types; in
338         * these situations the areEqual method helps quickly check for equality by potentially having special logic for
339         * the type this is meant to check. The body of implementations for this method can be fairly small; for byte
340         * arrays, it looks like: {@code return left == right
341         * || ((left instanceof byte[] && right instanceof byte[])
342         * ? Arrays.equals((byte[]) left, (byte[]) right)
343         * : Objects.equals(left, right));} , but for multidimensional arrays you should use the
344         * {@link #equalityHelper(Object[], Object[], IHasher)} method with an IHasher for the inner arrays that are 1D
345         * or otherwise already-hash-able, as can be seen in the body of the implementation for 2D char arrays, where
346         * charHasher is an existing IHasher that handles 1D arrays:
347         * {@code return left == right
348         * || ((left instanceof char[][] && right instanceof char[][])
349         * ? equalityHelper((char[][]) left, (char[][]) right, charHasher)
350         * : Objects.equals(left, right));}
351         *
352         * @param left  allowed to be null; most implementations will have special behavior for one type
353         * @param right allowed to be null; most implementations will have special behavior for one type
354         * @return true if left is equal to right (preferably by value, but reference equality may sometimes be needed)
355         */
356        boolean areEqual(final Object left, final Object right);
357    }
358
359    /**
360     * Not a general-purpose method; meant to ease implementation of {@link IHasher#areEqual(Object, Object)}
361     * methods when the type being compared is a multi-dimensional array (which normally requires the heavyweight method
362     * {@link Arrays#deepEquals(Object[], Object[])} or doing more work yourself; this reduces the work needed to
363     * implement fixed-depth equality). As mentioned in the docs for {@link IHasher#areEqual(Object, Object)}, example
364     * code that hashes 2D char arrays can be done using an IHasher for 1D char arrays called charHasher:
365     * {@code return left == right
366     * || ((left instanceof char[][] && right instanceof char[][])
367     * ? equalityHelper((char[][]) left, (char[][]) right, charHasher)
368     * : Objects.equals(left, right));}
369     *
370     * @param left an array of some kind of Object, usually an array, that the given IHasher can compare
371     * @param right an array of some kind of Object, usually an array, that the given IHasher can compare
372     * @param inner an IHasher to compare items in left with items in right
373     * @return true if the contents of left and right are equal by the given IHasher, otherwise false
374     */
375    public static boolean equalityHelper(Object[] left, Object[] right, IHasher inner) {
376        if (left == right)
377            return true;
378        if (left == null || right == null || left.length != right.length)
379            return false;
380        for (int i = 0; i < left.length; i++) {
381            if (!inner.areEqual(left[i], right[i]))
382                return false;
383        }
384        return true;
385    }

387    private static class BooleanHasher implements IHasher, Serializable {
388        private static final long serialVersionUID = 3L;
389
390        BooleanHasher() {
391        }
392
393        @Override
394        public int hash(final Object data) {
395            return (data instanceof boolean[]) ? CrossHash.hash((boolean[]) data) : data.hashCode();
396        }
397
398        @Override
399        public boolean areEqual(Object left, Object right) {
400            return left == right || ((left instanceof boolean[] && right instanceof boolean[]) ? Arrays.equals((boolean[]) left, (boolean[]) right) : Objects.equals(left, right));
401        }
402    }

730    private static class GeneralHasher implements IHasher, Serializable {
731        private static final long serialVersionUID = 3L;
732
733        GeneralHasher() {
734        }
735
736        @Override
737        public int hash(final Object data) {
738            return CrossHash.hash(data);
739        }
740
741        @Override
742        public boolean areEqual(Object left, Object right) {
743            if(left == right) return true;
744            Class l = left.getClass(), r = right.getClass();
745            if(l == r)
746            {
747                if(l.isArray())
748                {
749                    if(left instanceof int[]) return Arrays.equals((int[]) left, (int[]) right);
750                    else if(left instanceof long[]) return Arrays.equals((long[]) left, (long[]) right);
751                    else if(left instanceof char[]) return Arrays.equals((char[]) left, (char[]) right);
752                    else if(left instanceof double[]) return Arrays.equals((double[]) left, (double[]) right);
753                    else if(left instanceof boolean[]) return Arrays.equals((boolean[]) left, (boolean[]) right);
754                    else if(left instanceof byte[]) return Arrays.equals((byte[]) left, (byte[]) right);
755                    else if(left instanceof float[]) return Arrays.equals((float[]) left, (float[]) right);
756                    else if(left instanceof short[]) return Arrays.equals((short[]) left, (short[]) right);
757                    else if(left instanceof char[][]) return equalityHelper((char[][]) left, (char[][]) right, charHasher);
758                    else if(left instanceof int[][]) return equalityHelper((int[][]) left, (int[][]) right, intHasher);
759                    else if(left instanceof long[][]) return equalityHelper((long[][]) left, (long[][]) right, longHasher);
760                    else if(left instanceof CharSequence[]) return equalityHelper((CharSequence[]) left, (CharSequence[]) right, stringHasher);
761                    else if(left instanceof Object[]) return Arrays.equals((Object[]) left, (Object[]) right);
762                }
763                return Objects.equals(left, right);
764            }
765            return false;
766        }
767    }

775    /**
776     * A quick, simple hashing function that seems to have good results. Like LightRNG, it stores a state that
777     * it updates independently of the output, and this starts at a large prime. At each step, it takes the
778     * current item in the array being hashed, adds a large non-prime used in LightRNG's generation function
779     * (it's 2 to the 64, times the golden ratio phi, and truncated to a signed long), multiplies by a prime
780     * called the "state multiplier", adds the result to the state and stores it, multiplies the value of the
781     * state by another prime called the "output multiplier", then XORs the current result with that value
782     * before moving onto the next item in the array. A finalization step XORs the result with a complex value
783     * made by adding the state (left over from the previous step) to what was the output multiplier, adding
784     * the last known value for result to the phi-related constant from LightRNG, multiplying that pair, adding
785     * the initial state (which turns out to be unusually good for this, despite no particularly special numeric
786     * qualities other than being a probable prime) and then bitwise-rotating it left by a seemingly-random
787     * number drawn from the highest 6 bits of the state.
788     * <br>
789     * This all can be done very quickly; a million hashes of a million different 16-element long arrays can be
790     * computed in under 18-20 ms (in the benchmark, some amount of that is overhead from generating a new
791     * array with LongPeriodRNG, since the benchmark uses that RNG's state for data, and the default
792     * Arrays.hashCode implementation is only somewhat faster at under 16 ms). After several tries and tweaks
793     * to the constants this uses, it also gets remarkably few hash collisions. On the same 0x100000, or
794     * 1048576, RNG states for data, Lightning gets 110 collisions, the JDK Arrays.hashCode method gets 129
795     * collisions, Sip (implementing SipHash) gets 145 collisions, and CrossHash (using the FNV-1a algorithm)
796     * gets 135 collisions. Dispersion is not perfect, but
797     * at many bit sizes Lightning continues to have less collisions (it disperses better than the other hashes
798     * with several quantities of bits, at least on this test data). Lightning also does relatively well, though
799     * it isn't clearly ahead of the rest all the time, when hashing Strings, especially ones that use a larger
800     * set of letters, it seems (FakeLanguageGen was used to make test data, and languages that used more
801     * characters in their alphabet seemed to hash better with this than competing hashes for some reason).
802     * <br>
803     * There is certainly room for improvement with the specific numbers chosen; earlier versions used the
804     * state multiplier "Neely's number", which is a probable prime made by taking the radix-29 number
805     * "HARGNALLINSCLOPIOPEEPIO" (a reference to a very unusual TV show), truncating to 64 bits, and rotating
806     * right by 42 bits. This version uses "Neely's number" for an initial state and during finalization, and
807     * uses a different probable prime as the state multiplier, made with a similar process; it starts with the
808     * radix-36 number "EDSGERWDIJKSTRA", then does the same process but rotates right by 37 bits to obtain a
809     * different prime. This tweak seems to help with hash collisions. Extensive trial and error was used to
810     * find the current output multiplier, which has no real relationship to anything else but has exactly 32 of
811     * 64 bits set to 1, has 1 in the least and most significant bit indices (meaning it is negative and odd),
812     * and other than that seems to have better results on most inputs for mystifying reasons. Earlier versions
813     * applied a Gray code step to alter the output instead of a multiplier that heavily overflows to obfuscate
814     * state, but that had a predictable pattern for most of the inputs tried, which seemed less-than-ideal for
815     * a hash. Vitally, Lightning avoids predictable collisions that Arrays.hashCode has, like
816     * {@code Arrays.hashCode(new long[]{0})==Arrays.hashCode(new long[]{-1})}.
817     * <br>
818     * The output multiplier is 0xC6BC279692B5CC83L, the state multiplier is 0xD0E89D2D311E289FL, the number
819     * added to the state (from LightRNG and code derived from FastUtil, but obtained from the golden ratio
820     * phi) is 0x9E3779B97F4A7C15L, and the starting state ("Neely's Number") is 0x632BE59BD9B4E019L.
821     * <br>
822     * To help find patterns in hash output in a visual way, you can hash an x,y point, take the bottom 24 bits,
823     * and use that as an RGB color for the pixel at that x,y point. On a 512x512 grid of points, the patterns
824     * in Arrays.hashCode and the default CrossHash algorithm (FNV-1a) are evident, and Sip (implementing
825     * SipHash) does approximately as well as Lightning, with no clear patterns visible (Sip has been removed
826     * from SquidLib because it needs a lot of code and is slower than Mist). The
827     * idea is from a technical report on visual uses for hashing,
828     * http://www.clockandflame.com/media/Goulburn06.pdf .
829     * <ul>
830     * <li>{@link java.util.Arrays#hashCode(int[])}: http://i.imgur.com/S4Gh1sX.png</li>
831     * <li>{@link CrossHash#hash(int[])}: http://i.imgur.com/x8SDqvL.png</li>
832     * <li>(Former) CrossHash.Sip.hash(int[]): http://i.imgur.com/keSpIwm.png</li>
833     * <li>{@link CrossHash.Lightning#hash(int[])}: http://i.imgur.com/afGJ9cA.png</li>
834     * </ul>
835     */

1249    /**
1250     * The fastest hash in CrossHash, with middling quality. Uses a finely-tuned mix of very few operations for each
1251     * element, plus a minimal and simple finalization step, and as such obtains superior speed on the standard
1252     * benchmark SquidLib uses for hashes (hashing one million 16-element long arrays, remaining the best in both 32-bit
1253     * and 64-bit versions). Specifically, Wisp takes 9.478 ms to generate a million 64-bit hashes on a recent laptop
1254     * with an i7-6700HQ processor (removing the time the control takes to generate the million arrays). For comparison,
1255     * the JDK's Arrays.hashCode method takes 13.642 ms on the same workload, though it produces 32-bit hashes. Wisp
1256     * performs almost exactly as well producing 32-bit hashes as it does 64-bit hashes, where Hive slows down
1257     * significantly on some input types. This also passes visual tests where an earlier version of Wisp did not.
1258     * Collision rates are slightly worse than other CrossHash classes, but are better than the JDK's
1259     * Arrays.hashCode method, that is, acceptably low when given varied-enough inputs. On certain kinds of similar
1260     * inputs, Wisp will struggle with a higher collision rate. For example, when hashing Strings that contain only
1261     * several spaces, then some combination of digits 0-5, then more spaces, Wisp does very badly, worse than
1262     * {@link String#hashCode()} (which also does badly, though not as badly), while other hashes here do fine (such as
1263     * Water, which is the default for {@link CrossHash#hash(CharSequence)}).
1264     * <br>
1265     * This version replaces an older version of Wisp that had serious quality issues and wasn't quite as fast. Since
1266     * the only reason one would use the older version was speed without regard for quality, and it was marked as Beta,
1267     * a faster version makes sense to replace the slower one, rather than add yet another nested class in CrossHash.
1268     * <br>
1269     * Wisp is no longer considered Beta-quality, but even though it is rather fast, it has some cases where categories
1270     * of input cause frequent collisions. {@link Water} is about 20% slower but doesn't have such categories of
1271     * pathologically bad inputs, and passes tests that Wisp fails badly on. Because the hash-based collections in
1272     * SquidLib need a pretty good hash function to work at their best (they use linear-probing with open addressing,
1273     * which struggles when hashes are bad), 20% loss of speed during hashing to avoid slower
1274     * lookups/insertions/deletions from {@link OrderedMap}, {@link OrderedSet}, {@link UnorderedMap},
1275     * {@link UnorderedSet}, {@link Arrangement}, and others is probably worth it; if you really need speed then Wisp is
1276     * right here.
1277     */

1962    /**
1963     * A whole cluster of Wisp-like hash functions that sacrifice a small degree of speed, but can be built with up
1964     * to 128 bits of salt values that help to obscure what hashing function is actually being used. This class is
1965     * similar to the older Storm variety, but is somewhat faster and has many more possible salt "states" when using
1966     * the constructors that take two longs or a CharSequence. There isn't really any reason to use Storm, so Mist has
1967     * now replaced Storm entirely. Code that used Storm should be able to just change any usage of "Storm" to "Mist".
1968     * <br>
1969     * The salt fields are not serialized, so it is important that the same salt will be given by the
1970     * program when the same hash results are wanted for some inputs.
1971     * <br>
1972     * A group of 48 static, final, pre-initialized Mist members are present in this class, 24 with the
1973     * name of a letter in the Greek alphabet (this uses the convention on Wikipedia,
1974     * https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_alphabet#Letters , where lambda is spelled with a 'b') and 24 with the same
1975     * name followed by an underscore, such as {@link #alpha_}. The whole group of 48 pre-initialized members are also
1976     * present in a static array called {@code predefined}. These can be useful when, for example, you want to get
1977     * multiple hashes of a single array or String as part of cuckoo hashing or similar techniques that need multiple
1978     * hashes for the same inputs.
1979     */

2499    /**
2500     * A reasonably-fast hashing function that passes some of SMHasher's quality tests, but neither critically fails nor
2501     * overwhelmingly succeeds the full SMHasher test battery. This was the default used by methods in the
2502     * outer class like {@link CrossHash#hash(int[])}, but it has been replaced there by {@link Water}; you should
2503     * prefer using the outer class since this inner class is only here for reference. The one advantage Hive has over
2504     * Water is potentially better optimization for GWT, but since the main usage of CrossHash is for 64-bit hashes, GWT
2505     * will be slow regardless for that usage.
2506     * <br>
2507     * This mixes three different algorithms: the main one is used whenever inputs or outputs are 64-bit (so, all
2508     * hash64() overloads and {@link Hive#hash(long[])} for long and double), a modification of the main one to perform
2509     * better on GWT (only used on hash() overloads, and only when inputs are individually 32-bit or less), and
2510     * a simpler algorithm (which was called Jolt) for hash64() on boolean and byte data.
2511     * <br>
2512     * Speed-wise, the main algorithm is about 20% slower than Wisp, but in hash tables it doesn't have clear failure 
2513     * cases like Wisp does on some inputs (such as fixed-length Strings with identical prefixes). If collisions are
2514     * expensive or profiling shows that Wisp's algorithm is colliding at a high rate, you should probably use the
2515     * normal IHasher and CrossHash.hash() methods, since those will use Hive. The modified algorithm for GWT is a
2516     * little slower than the main algorithm in the C++ implementation that was used to check SMHasher quality, but it
2517     * may perform similarly to the main algorithm in Java on desktop platforms. Since it avoids creating longs or doing
2518     * any math on them, it should be at least 3x faster than the main algorithm on GWT (a GWT long is internally
2519     * represented by 3 JS numbers, so barring special optimizations it takes at least 3x as many math operations to use
2520     * longs there).
2521     * <br>
2522     * Its design uses two states like {@link Lightning} or {@link Wisp}, updating them differently from each other, and
2523     * bitwise-rotates one at each step. It combines the states (xorshifting one state, multiplying it by a huge
2524     * constant, and adding that to the other state) and then runs that through MurmurHash3's finalization function (its
2525     * {@code fmix64()} function; the main algorithm elides one xorshift at the end that proved unnecessary). Parts of
2526     * the code here are inspired by the design of {@link DiverRNG}, particularly its determine() method since both
2527     * use an XLCG (XOR Linear Congruential Generator, as PractRand calls it) as a processing step.
2528     * <br>
2529     * The name comes from the song I was listening to when I finally got the tests to pass ("Slave The Hive" by High On
2530     * Fire) and from the wide assortment of code that I had to employ to achieve a SMHasher successful run (which
2531     * turned out to be not-so-successful).
2532     */

3237    /**
3238     * A fairly fast hashing algorithm in general, Water performs especially well on large arrays, and passes SMHasher's
3239     * newest and most stringent version of tests. The int-hashing {@link #hash(int[])} method is almost twice as fast
3240     * as {@link CrossHash#hash(int[])} and faster than {@link Arrays#hashCode(int[])}. Based on
3241     * <a href="https://github.com/wangyi-fudan/wyhash">wyhash</a>, specifically
3242     * <a href="https://github.com/tommyettinger/waterhash">the waterhash variant</a>. This version passes SMHasher for
3243     * both the 32-bit output hash() methods and the 64-bit output hash64() methods (which use the slightly tweaked
3244     * wheathash variant in the waterhash Git repo, or woothash for hashing long arrays). While an earlier version
3245     * passed rurban/smhasher, it failed demerphq/smhasher (Yves' more stringent fork), so some minor tweaks allowed the
3246     * latest code to pass Yves' test. Uses 64-bit math, so it won't be as fast on GWT. Currently, the methods that hash
3247     * types other than int arrays aren't as fast as the int array hash, but they are usually faster than the former
3248     * default Hive implementation, and unlike Hive, these pass SMHasher.
3249     * <br>
3250     * These hash functions are so fast because they operate in bulk on 4 items at a time, such as 4 ints (which is the
3251     * optimal case), 4 bytes, or 4 longs (which uses a different algorithm). This bulk operation usually entails 3
3252     * multiplications and some other, cheaper operations per 4 items hashed. For long arrays, it requires many more
3253     * multiplications, but modern CPUs can pipeline the operations on unrelated longs to run in parallel on one core.
3254     * If any items are left over after the bulk segment, Water uses the least effort possible to hash the remaining 1,
3255     * 2, or 3 items left. Most of these operations use the method {@link #mum(long, long)}, which helps take two inputs
3256     * and multiply them once, getting a more-random result after another small step. The long array code uses
3257     * {@link #wow(long, long)} (similar to mum upside-down), which mixes up its arguments with each other before
3258     * multplying. It finishes with either code similar to mum() for 32-bit output hash() methods, or a somewhat more
3259     * rigorous method for 64-bit output hash64() methods (still similar to mum).
3260     */
3261    @SuppressWarnings("NumericOverflow")
3262    public static final class Water {
3263        /**
3264         * Big constant 0.
3265         */
3266        public static final long b0 = 0xA0761D6478BD642FL;

3288        /**
3289         * Takes two arguments that are technically longs, and should be very different, and uses them to get a result
3290         * that is technically a long and mixes the bits of the inputs. The arguments and result are only technically
3291         * longs because their lower 32 bits matter much more than their upper 32, and giving just any long won't work.
3292         * <br>
3293         * This is very similar to wyhash's mum function, but doesn't use 128-bit math because it expects that its
3294         * arguments are only relevant in their lower 32 bits (allowing their product to fit in 64 bits).
3295         * @param a a long that should probably only hold an int's worth of data
3296         * @param b a long that should probably only hold an int's worth of data
3297         * @return a sort-of randomized output dependent on both inputs
3298         */
3299        public static long mum(final long a, final long b) {
3300            final long n = a * b;
3301            return n - (n >>> 32);
3302        }

3304        /**
3305         * A slower but higher-quality variant on {@link #mum(long, long)} that can take two arbitrary longs (with any
3306         * of their 64 bits containing relevant data) instead of mum's 32-bit sections of its inputs, and outputs a
3307         * 64-bit result that can have any of its bits used.
3308         * <br>
3309         * This was changed so it distributes bits from both inputs a little better on July 6, 2019.
3310         * @param a any long
3311         * @param b any long
3312         * @return a sort-of randomized output dependent on both inputs
3313         */
3314        public static long wow(final long a, final long b) {
3315            final long n = (a ^ (b << 39 | b >>> 25)) * (b ^ (a << 39 | a >>> 25));
3316            return n ^ (n >>> 32);
3317        }

4127     * Like Mist, this is a class for hash functors, each an object with a 64-bit long seed, but it uses about the same
4128     * algorithm as {@link Water} instead of the older, less-robust style Mist uses. Has a lot of predefined functors
4129     * (192, named after 24 Greek letters and 72 Goetic demons, see
4130     * <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lesser_Key_of_Solomon#The_Seventy-Two_Demons">Wikipedia for the demons</a>,
4131     * in both lower case and lower case with a trailing underscore). You probably want to use {@link #predefined}
4132     * instead of wrangling demon names; you can always choose an element from predefined with a 7-bit number, and there
4133     * are 64 numbers outside that range so you can choose any of those when a functor must be different.
4134     * <br>
4135     * The seed a Yolk object is constructed with cannot change; it is expected to be reused at least a little bit, and
4136     * it only performs a "scrambling" step on the seed once per Yolk (scramble, Yolk, get it?). If you want to have the
4137     * flexibility to change seeds at-will, and you don't mind the reasonably-efficient scrambling step being performed
4138     * every hash, you can use the static methods on this class, like {@link #hash64(long, CharSequence)} and
4139     * {@link #hash(long, CharSequence)}. For these you can give any long seed as a first parameter, then the normal
4140     * argument to hash. The static methods use the same algorithm as passing the seed to {@link #Yolk(long)} and

4245                seed = mum(
